# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aquatic-ecosystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/a-directory-of-important-wetlands-in-australia] The directory uses a classification system consisting of the following three categories (i.e.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The radio art of Schafer and his colleague, has found expression in many different fields.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] While most have taken some inspiration from Schafer's writings, in recent years there have also been divergences from the initial ideas.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The expanded expressions of acoustic ecology are increasing due to the sonic impacts of road and airport construction that affect the soundscapes in and around cities where the human population is more dense.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] There has also been a broadening of bioacoustics (the use of sound by animals) to consider the subjective and objective responses of animals to human noise, with ocean noise capturing the most attention.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology can also be informative of changes in the climate or other environmental changes since every day we listen to sounds in the world to identify their source such as bird, car, plane, wind, water.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] But we don't listen those sounds as a network, a mesh of relationships that form an ecology.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology finds expression in many different fields that characterize a soundscape, which are biophony, geophony, and anthrophony.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Noise is generally a by-product of increased urbanization and development.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] As our cities became more industrialized, the volume and frequency of anthrophony, man-made noise signals, increased.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Noise can alter the acoustic environment of aquatic and terrestrial habitats.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Animal biodiversity has shown to decline because of chronic noise levels in cities and along roadways.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Musician and soundscape ecologist Bernie Krause relates biophony to an orchestra, where different groups of animals in an environment make sounds at different levels to avoid overlap or competition in their communication.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Manmade noise such as jets flying over a habitat can disrupt the natural order of these sounds, even putting certain species in danger of predators.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] For example, some frogs synchronize in a way that protects individuals from attracting attention.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The noise of a jet can cause the frogs to stop or fall out of sync, temporarily breaking this effect and exposing them to other animals.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] On land, animal communication is shaped by physical characteristics of an environment such as distance, range of vision, weather, and surrounding noise.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The physical layout of a habitat may impede the spread of soundwaves while air conditions can affect sound quality and speed.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Animals can adapt to factors like distance by adjusting the frequency and amplitute of their calls to maximize communication effectiveness.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Some species such as the urban great tits have changed the frequency of their calls to adapt.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes of particular habitats are always evolving because the activities and species that exist in those habitats changes over time.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] In terms of evolution, man-made noise is a much more recent phenomenon.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Indeed, through investigating collected recordings, ecologists can study ethology of animal acoustic communication, evolution, and development of acoustic behavior, relationships between animal sounds and their environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] However, all those ecological research goals have a precondition that those bioacoustic recordings are well investigated so that the animal species can be accurately recognized.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Scientific research has shown that it has potential to change behavior, alter physiology and even restructure animal communities.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes are composed of the anthrophony, geophony and biophony of a particular environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] They are specific to location and change over time.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology aims to study the relationship between these things, i.e. the relationship between humans, animals and nature, within these soundscapes.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] These relationships are delicate and subject to disruption by natural or man-made means.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] In his book *The Tuning of the World*, Schafer used new terms like 'soundmarks' -- a specific community's distinctive sounds—and 'keynotes' -- prevalent but overlooked background sounds such as traffic—to help categorize the different elements of a soundscape.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Biophony is the study of sounds emerging from animal sources, like whale vocalizations or birdsong.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Geophony can be defined as the sounds originating from the Earth's natural processes, such as the blowing of wind or movement of waves.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Anthrophony is the soundscape defined by man-made sources, like speech or road noise.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Research on the relationship between visual and auditory experiences in urban settings finds that the positive or negative visual perceptions of a landscape can directly affect the emotional assessment of the location's soundscape.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] A pleasant view or comfortable surroundings can increase people's tolerance and even appreciation for the sounds of an environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] People's preferences for noise control have been shown to differ based on the culture and technology of the time period as well as the familiarity or practicality of certain sounds.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] For example, accepted sources of loud noise such as church bells or trucks may not bother a neighborhood as much as someone's new leaf blower, even if it is not as loud as more familiar sounds.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] This is why it is considered difficult to generalize which sounds are unwanted in a community.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Studying the soundscapes and traumatic impact of war has shown the effectiveness of noise as a psychological weapon to produce fear.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Aircraft activity has been a continuing development around the world and has some very good potential to change social-ecological systems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] In Alaska, for example the communities are reporting that the aircraft disturb wildlife and negatively influence harvest practices and experiences.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The limited data has some restricted knowledge about the extent of aircraft activity over traditional harvest areas.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] It is actually very impressive to see the amount of aircraft overflight around the rural subsistence, because the activity is increasing significantly and they have reached a median of 12 overflights per day near human development, which is six times greater than undeveloped areas.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Therefore, those planes startle caribou prefer to avoid aircraft themselves, which has a result that they will need to go farther to do a better harvest, but this will occur in adding some costs for fuel, equipment, and the effort for sure.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Those kind of examples help to understand the impact on social-ecological dynamics in Antarctica.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The ambient noise present within the world's oceans; geophonic, anthrophonic, and biophonic, has been identified as a critical indicator to the well-being of the regional biosphere.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The acoustic niche hypothesis, as proposed by acoustic ecologist Bernie Krause in 1993, refers to the process in which organisms partition the acoustic domain, finding their own niche in frequency and/or time in order to communicate without competition from other species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The theory draws from the ideas of niche differentiation and can be used to predict differences between young and mature ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Similar to how interspecific competition can place limits on the number of coexisting species that can utilize a given availability of habitats or resources, the available acoustic space in an environment is a limited resource that is partitioned among those species competing to utilize it.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] In mature ecosystems, species will sing at unique bandwidths and specific times, displaying a lack of interspecies competition in the acoustic environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Conversely, in young ecosystems, one is more likely to encounter multiple species using similar frequency bandwidths, which can result in interference between their respective calls, or a complete lack of activity in uncontested bandwidths.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Biological invasions can also result in interference in the acoustic niche, with non-native species altering the dynamics of the native community by producing signals that mask or degrade native signals.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] This can cause a variety of ecological impacts, such as decreased reproduction, aggressive interactions, and altered predator-prey dynamics.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] The degree of partitioning in an environment can be used to indicate ecosystem health and biodiversity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] "Dominion" uses Canadian soundmarks that were made in different province by the World Soundscape Project at Simon Fraser University for an event of cross-country tour that happened in 1973.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] What is interesting about those sounds is that they are stretched over the time, so the extended versions allowed the people that listen to the sound in a more harmonic way.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Those unique sound signals, were picked up by the live performers and then amplified to give the best experience possible to his audience.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] This is a subfield of archeology and acoustics that in general study the relation between people and sound along the history.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] This is an interdisciplinary field that has methodological contributions from acoustics, archeology and computer simulation.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Many cultures explored through archaeology were mostly focused on the oral, which lead the researchers to believe that studying the sonic nature of archaeological sites and artifacts may reveal new information on the civilization being scrutinized.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] Moglen (2007) recreated pre-historical Soundscapes (Acoustic Ecology) at University of California, Berkeley's Department of Anthropology, combining compositional techniques with site recordings for a non-diegetic piece in the virtual world of Second Life, on "Okapi Island" .
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acoustic-ecology] At the Center for New Media the acoustic ecological setting of the former jazz scene in Oakland, CA was developed for a virtual world setting.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] The **acrotelm** is one of two distinct layers in undisturbed peat bogs.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] The boundary between the two layers is defined by the transition from peat containing living plants (acrotelm) to peat containing dead plant material (catotelm).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] This typically coincides with the lowest level of the water table.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] To lower the water table before harvesting, ditching is performed first.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] Fluctuations in the position of the water table in a peat bog occur within the acrotelm, and hence conditions may vary from aerobic to anaerobic with time.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] Where there are extensive geological fluctuations in the peatland surface, the depth of the acrotelm may change fundamentally over a couple of meters of distance.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] In general, the acrotelm has a higher hydraulic conductivity and a lower bulk density than the catotelm.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] Other characteristics are shared by these two zones.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] After ditching, the acrotelm becomes thicker and more effective, drying the peat and simplifying harvesting.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] Drainage and subsidence lower the elevation of the peat surface, significantly lowering the soil's hydraulic conductivity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] Completely developed acrotelm, only found in ombrotrophic bogs, make it possible to study atmospheric deposition and how it affects ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/acrotelm] Through the relatively quick disintegration of the acrotelm, only a small portion of the total nutrients locked up in the plant material are mineralized, making them available for additional plant development inclusive of bacterial and fungal activity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] An **aquatic ecosystem** is an ecosystem found in and around a body of water, in contrast to land-based terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Aquatic ecosystems contain communities of organisms—**aquatic life**—that are dependent on each other and on their environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The two main types of aquatic ecosystems are marine ecosystems and freshwater ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater ecosystems may be lentic (slow moving water, including pools, ponds, and lakes); lotic (faster moving water, for example streams and rivers); and wetlands (areas where the soil is saturated or inundated for at least part of the time).
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine ecosystems are the largest of Earth's aquatic ecosystems and exist in waters that have a high salt content.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] These systems contrast with freshwater ecosystems, which have a lower salt content.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine waters cover more than 70% of the surface of the Earth and account for more than 97% of Earth's water supply and 90% of habitable space on Earth.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Seawater has an average salinity of 35 parts per thousand of water.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Actual salinity varies among different marine ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine ecosystems can be divided into many zones depending upon water depth and shoreline features.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The oceanic zone is the vast open part of the ocean where animals such as whales, sharks, and tuna live.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The benthic zone consists of substrates below water where many invertebrates live.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The intertidal zone is the area between high and low tides.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Other near-shore (neritic) zones can include mudflats, seagrass meadows, mangroves, rocky intertidal systems, salt marshes, coral reefs, kelp forests and lagoons.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] In the deep water, hydrothermal vents may occur where chemosynthetic sulfur bacteria form the base of the food web.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] A marine coastal ecosystem is a marine ecosystem which occurs where the land meets the ocean.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Worldwide there is about 620,000 kilometres (390,000 mi) of coastline.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Coastal habitats extend to the margins of the continental shelves, occupying about 7 percent of the ocean surface area.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine coastal ecosystems include many very different types of marine habitats, each with their own characteristics and species composition.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] They are characterized by high levels of biodiversity and productivity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Organisms that live freely at the ocean surface, termed neuston, include keystone organisms like the golden seaweed *Sargassum* that makes up the Sargasso Sea, floating barnacles, marine snails, nudibranchs, and cnidarians.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Many ecologically and economically important fish species live as or rely upon neuston.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Species at the surface are not distributed uniformly; the ocean's surface provides habitat for unique neustonic communities and ecoregions found at only certain latitudes and only in specific ocean basins.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] But the surface is also on the front line of climate change and pollution.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Life on the ocean's surface connects worlds.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] From shallow waters to the deep sea, the open ocean to rivers and lakes, numerous terrestrial and marine species depend on the surface ecosystem and the organisms found there.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater ecosystems are a subset of Earth's aquatic ecosystems that include the biological communities inhabiting freshwater waterbodies such as lakes, ponds, rivers, streams, springs, bogs, and wetlands.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] They can be contrasted with marine ecosystems, which have a much higher salinity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater habitats can be classified by different factors, including temperature, light penetration, nutrients, and vegetation.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] A lake ecosystem or lacustrine ecosystem includes biotic (living) plants, animals and micro-organisms, as well as abiotic (non-living) physical and chemical interactions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Lake ecosystems are a prime example of lentic ecosystems (*lentic* refers to stationary or relatively still freshwater, from the Latin *lentus*, which means "sluggish"), which include ponds, lakes and wetlands, and much of this article applies to lentic ecosystems in general.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Lentic ecosystems can be compared with lotic ecosystems, which involve flowing terrestrial waters such as rivers and streams.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Together, these two ecosystems are examples of freshwater ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Lentic systems are diverse, ranging from a small, temporary rainwater pool a few inches deep to Lake Baikal, which has a maximum depth of 1642 m.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The general distinction between pools/ponds and lakes is vague, but Brown states that ponds and pools have their entire bottom surfaces exposed to light, while lakes do not.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] In addition, some lakes become seasonally stratified.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Ponds and pools have two regions: the pelagic open water zone, and the benthic zone, which comprises the bottom and shore regions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Since lakes have deep bottom regions not exposed to light, these systems have an additional zone, the profundal.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] These three areas can have very different abiotic conditions and, hence, host species that are specifically adapted to live there.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] River ecosystems are flowing waters that drain the landscape, and include the biotic (living) interactions amongst plants, animals and micro-organisms, as well as abiotic (nonliving) physical and chemical interactions of its many parts.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] River ecosystems are part of larger watershed networks or catchments, where smaller headwater streams drain into mid-size streams, which progressively drain into larger river networks.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The major zones in river ecosystems are determined by the river bed's gradient or by the velocity of the current.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Faster moving turbulent water typically contains greater concentrations of dissolved oxygen, which supports greater biodiversity than the slow-moving water of pools.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] These distinctions form the basis for the division of rivers into upland and lowland rivers.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The food base of streams within riparian forests is mostly derived from the trees, but wider streams and those that lack a canopy derive the majority of their food base from algae.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Anadromous fish are also an important source of nutrients.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Environmental threats to rivers include loss of water, dams, chemical pollution and introduced species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] A dam produces negative effects that continue down the watershed.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The most important negative effects are the reduction of spring flooding, which damages wetlands, and the retention of sediment, which leads to the loss of deltaic wetlands.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] A wetland is a distinct semi-aquatic ecosystem whose groundcovers are flooded or saturated in water, either permanently, for years or decades, or only seasonally.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Flooding results in oxygen-poor (anoxic) processes taking place, especially in the soils.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Wetlands form a transitional zone between waterbodies and dry lands, and are different from other terrestrial or aquatic ecosystems due to their vegetation's roots having adapted to oxygen-poor waterlogged soils.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] They are considered among the most biologically diverse of all ecosystems, serving as habitats to a wide range of aquatic and semi-aquatic plants and animals, with often improved water quality due to plant removal of excess nutrients such as nitrates and phosphorus.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Aquatic ecosystems perform many important environmental functions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, they recycle nutrients, purify water, attenuate floods, recharge ground water and provide habitats for wildlife.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The biota of an aquatic ecosystem contribute to its self-purification, most notably microorganisms, phytoplankton, higher plants, invertebrates, fish, bacteria, protists, aquatic fungi, and more.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] These organisms are actively involved in multiple self-purification processes, including organic matter destruction and water filtration.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] It is crucial that aquatic ecosystems are reliably self-maintained, as they also provide habitats for species that reside in them.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] In addition to environmental functions, aquatic ecosystems are also used for human recreation, and are very important to the tourism industry, especially in coastal regions.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] They are also used for religious purposes, such as religious tourism to the Jordan River by Christians, and educational purposes, such as the usage of lakes for ecological study.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The biotic characteristics are mainly determined by the organisms that occur.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, wetland plants may produce dense canopies that cover large areas of sediment or snails or geese may graze the vegetation leaving large mud flats.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Aquatic environments have relatively low oxygen levels, forcing adaptation by the organisms found there.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, many wetland plants must produce aerenchyma to carry oxygen to roots.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Other biotic characteristics are more subtle and difficult to measure, such as the relative importance of competition, mutualism or predation.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] There are a growing number of cases where predation by coastal herbivores including snails, geese and mammals appears to be a dominant biotic factor.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Autotrophic organisms are producers that generate organic compounds from inorganic material.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Algae use solar energy to generate biomass from carbon dioxide and are possibly the most important autotrophic organisms in aquatic environments.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The more shallow the water, the greater the biomass contribution from rooted and floating vascular plants.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] These two sources combine to produce the extraordinary production of estuaries and wetlands, as this autotrophic biomass is converted into fish, birds, amphibians and other aquatic species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Chemosynthetic bacteria are found in benthic marine ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] These organisms are able to feed on hydrogen sulfide in water that comes from volcanic vents.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Great concentrations of animals that feed on these bacteria are found around volcanic vents.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, there are giant tube worms (*Riftia pachyptila*) 1.5 m in length and clams (*Calyptogena magnifica*) 30 cm long.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Heterotrophic organisms consume autotrophic organisms and use the organic compounds in their bodies as energy sources and as raw materials to create their own biomass.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Euryhaline organisms are salt tolerant and can survive in marine ecosystems, while stenohaline or salt intolerant species can only live in freshwater environments.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] An ecosystem is composed of biotic communities that are structured by biological interactions and abiotic environmental factors.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Some of the important abiotic environmental factors of aquatic ecosystems include substrate type, water depth, nutrient levels, temperature, salinity, and flow.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] It is often difficult to determine the relative importance of these factors without rather large experiments.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] There may be complicated feedback loops.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, sediment may determine the presence of aquatic plants, but aquatic plants may also trap sediment, and add to the sediment through peat.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The amount of dissolved oxygen in a water body is frequently the key substance in determining the extent and kinds of organic life in the water body.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Fish need dissolved oxygen to survive, although their tolerance to low oxygen varies among species; in extreme cases of low oxygen, some fish even resort to air gulping.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Plants often have to produce aerenchyma, while the shape and size of leaves may also be altered.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Conversely, oxygen is fatal to many kinds of anaerobic bacteria.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Nutrient levels are important in controlling the abundance of many species of algae.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The relative abundance of nitrogen and phosphorus can in effect determine which species of algae come to dominate.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Algae are a very important source of food for aquatic life, but at the same time, if they become over-abundant, they can cause declines in fish when they decay.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Similar over-abundance of algae in coastal environments such as the Gulf of Mexico produces, upon decay, a hypoxic region of water known as a dead zone.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The salinity of the water body is also a determining factor in the kinds of species found in the water body.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Organisms in marine ecosystems tolerate salinity, while many freshwater organisms are intolerant of salt.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The degree of salinity in an estuary or delta is an important control upon the type of wetland (fresh, intermediate, or brackish), and the associated animal species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Dams built upstream may reduce spring flooding, and reduce sediment accretion, and may therefore lead to saltwater intrusion in coastal wetlands.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater used for irrigation purposes often absorbs levels of salt that are harmful to freshwater organisms.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The health of an aquatic ecosystem is degraded when the ecosystem's ability to absorb a stress has been exceeded.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] A stress on an aquatic ecosystem can be a result of physical, chemical or biological alterations to the environment.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Physical alterations include changes in water temperature, water flow and light availability.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Chemical alterations include changes in the loading rates of biostimulatory nutrients, oxygen-consuming materials, and toxins.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Biological alterations include over-harvesting of commercial species and the introduction of exotic species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Human populations can impose excessive stresses on aquatic ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Climate change driven by anthropogenic activities can harm aquatic ecosystems by disrupting current distribution patterns of plants and animals.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] It has negatively impacted deep sea biodiversity, coastal fish diversity, crustaceans, coral reefs, and other biotic components of these ecosystems.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Human-made aquatic ecosystems, such as ditches, aquaculture ponds, and irrigation channels, may also cause harm to naturally occurring ecosystems by trading off biodiversity with their intended purposes.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] For instance, ditches are primarily used for drainage, but their presence also negatively affects biodiversity.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] There are many examples of excessive stresses with negative consequences.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The environmental history of the Great Lakes of North America illustrates this problem, particularly how multiple stresses, such as water pollution, over-harvesting and invasive species can combine.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] The Norfolk Broadlands in England illustrate similar decline with pollution and invasive species.
[src:aquatic-ecosystem/aquatic-ecosystem] Lake Pontchartrain along the Gulf of Mexico illustrates the negative effects of different stresses including levee construction, logging of swamps, invasive species and salt water intrusion.
